Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Core, seed, and thinly slice the @red bell pepper{1}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice the @yellow onion{1}. Cut the @Yukon Gold potatoes{12%oz} into ½-inch cubes. Finely chop the @cilantro{¼%oz}. Cut the @lemon{1} into wedges. Mince or grate the @garlic{2%cloves}.

Toss the potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Place in the oven and roast for ~{20-25%minutes}, until golden brown.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add the @green beans{4%oz}, onion, bell pepper and garlic. Cook, tossing for ~{7-8%minutes}, until softened and slightly blistered. Stir in half the chopped cilantro, season with salt and pepper, and set aside.

In the same pan, heat another drizzle of olive oil over medium-high heat. Season the @tilapia{12%oz} on all sides with the @blackening spice{1%tbsp}, salt, and pepper. Add the fish to the pan and cook for ~{2-3%minutes} per side, until cooked through and slightly blackened.

Plate the crispy potatoes and blistered vegetables, then top with the blackened tilapia. Serve with the lemon wedges and a sprinkle of the remaining cilantro, enjoy!

> For a lighter preparation, we're blackening this flaky fish with a potent mix of spices rather than batter frying.

> A side of crispy roasted potatoes and caramelized vegetables is the perfect accompaniment.